<div id="review_1296600772" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1296600772" />
    <a title="Dermot Davis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14715659-dermot-davis"><img alt="Dermot Davis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442647280p2/14715659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1296600772?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dermot Davis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dermot Davis" href="/user/show/14715659-dermot-davis">Dermot Davis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1296600772" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14851376823211275200">Alone, lonely and heart-sick, Morgan Stanfield travels to Russia thinking that he is in search of love when all this time he has been in search of himself. Writing honestly to the point of cringe-worthy embarrassment, this (faux?) memoir does not spare us the naked thoughts of a deeply troubled and vulnerable man as he sees his forties approach and he fears that he will never experience love in this life that is speeding by so fast. As a gullible and naive traveler to a land filled with contrast</span>
  <span id="freeText14851376823211275200" style="display:none">Alone, lonely and heart-sick, Morgan Stanfield travels to Russia thinking that he is in search of love when all this time he has been in search of himself. Writing honestly to the point of cringe-worthy embarrassment, this (faux?) memoir does not spare us the naked thoughts of a deeply troubled and vulnerable man as he sees his forties approach and he fears that he will never experience love in this life that is speeding by so fast. As a gullible and naive traveler to a land filled with contrasts he witnesses first-hand the best and worst that humanity has to offer. Provided friendship by the genuinely warm-hearted he is equally preyed upon by the mean-spirited and opportunistic but one of his nicest attributes (and he has many) is that he never gives up on the human race, or indeed, most importantly, himself. I can see him returning to the land of warmth and cold and being less naive and gullible and - more critically - being more sure of himself, he is bound to find what he, all along, has been looking for. I would love to read that sequel and see what it is that he finds.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14851376823211275200" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


