<div id="review_1404616184" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1404616184" />
    <a title="B.J. Robinson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5841874-b-j-robinson"><img alt="B.J. Robinson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442944959p2/5841874.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1404616184?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="B.J. Robinson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="B.J. Robinson" href="/user/show/5841874-b-j-robinson">B.J. Robinson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Memoir Readers</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to B.J. by: </span>
      Author
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1404616184" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11551476774641044347">Morgan is searching for love and feels he&apos;ll only find it in a Russian woman. He&apos;s in his thirties, a California man desperate to find true love, but he is set on certain ideals. The book is well written and easy to read, in a conversational tone. The author has a style all his own which makes the memoir a worthy read and memorable. From his poetic beginning to the last when he discovers his own truth, it&apos;s a book a reader will enjoy. He flew to Russia for to find true love. Will he come back wi</span>
  <span id="freeText11551476774641044347" style="display:none">Morgan is searching for love and feels he'll only find it in a Russian woman. He's in his thirties, a California man desperate to find true love, but he is set on certain ideals. The book is well written and easy to read, in a conversational tone. The author has a style all his own which makes the memoir a worthy read and memorable. From his poetic beginning to the last when he discovers his own truth, it's a book a reader will enjoy. He flew to Russia for to find true love. Will he come back with it? My favorite line in the book is, "It's too bad we can't choose who we love." Insightful. Brings us to that age-old question is it better to have loved and lost than to never have loved at all? To know love and lose it, is it worth it? From the opening in the digs where two skeletons are found in an unusual position to the last pages when the plane leaves the Russian runway, the book is thought-provoking and insightful and leaves the reader to ponder and discover his own truth. Sometimes we must lose ideals to find true, lasting love, but can Morgan give up his? Brings me to mind of an old country song about the man's baby being made in the USA. Makes me wonder if Morgan couldn't have pursued a different part of it rather than California? The USA is a multicolored patchwork quilt, offering a gumbo of women of different cultures, as different as night and day. All women in the USA are not like California ones. Morgan has a friend he talks with named Kim, who offers him guidance and act like a mom to him, though a young one, but will her guidance be enough to help him find that true, lasting love he's searching for? Is it out there? Is it in Russia as his mind is set on, or could it possibly be in a place he never thought to look? They say don't search for love; it will find you. Really enjoyed this journey through Morgan's mind.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11551476774641044347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


