<div id="review_1386522131" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1386522131" />
    <a title="Donna Crow" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3407123-donna-crow"><img alt="Donna Crow" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521853887p2/3407123.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1386522131?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Donna Crow" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Donna Crow" href="/user/show/3407123-donna-crow">Donna Crow</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1386522131" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2923556509887188209">From Afar starts out reading like chick lit for men—fun, funny and lighthearted. The serious side sneaks up on the reader as you begin to realize how profound the hero’s wry observations about love really are—and how eye-opening his experiences with the electronic dating world. And then Morgan sets out for Russia and the novel takes on aspects of a thoroughly engaging travelogue. I love writers whose powers of description can put me in the scene of the action so I can experience the whole advent</span>
  <span id="freeText2923556509887188209" style="display:none">From Afar starts out reading like chick lit for men—fun, funny and lighthearted. The serious side sneaks up on the reader as you begin to realize how profound the hero’s wry observations about love really are—and how eye-opening his experiences with the electronic dating world. And then Morgan sets out for Russia and the novel takes on aspects of a thoroughly engaging travelogue. I love writers whose powers of description can put me in the scene of the action so I can experience the whole adventure with the hero. Frank Scozzari is one of those writers. After reading From Afar I feel I’ve been to Russia and experienced the best and the worst of its people and culture. Finally, there’s the coming of age aspect to the story—always one of my favorite literary genres. Granted, Morgan is a bit old to be coming of age, but in any novel—and especially a quest, which From Afar is—the hero needs to grow and experience some enobling. Morgan does this in spades. I fervently wish him and his creator the very best.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2923556509887188209" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


